        <body>
            <entry xml:id="entry_jæw" xml:lang="os">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>jæw</orth></form>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>просо</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>proso millet</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к иран. *%iyava-%i. Общеиранское и индоевропейское
                    слово. Применялось к различным злакам. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ku"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ku"><w>yō</w></mentioned>,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="hac"><lang/>
                        <w>yāu</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_KPF"
                            /><biblScope>Abt. III, Bd. II, стр. 463</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
                        xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"><w>jō</w>
                        <gloss><q>ячмень</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/>
                        <w>уōu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgy"><lang/>
                        <w>уоu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="isk"><lang/>
                        <w>уau</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="srh"><lang/>
                        <w>zau</w>
                        <gloss><q>хлеб в зерне</q></gloss></mentioned> (?), <mentioned
                        xml:lang="wbl"><lang/>
                        <w>zau</w></mentioned> id., <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"><lang/>
                        <w>jawaus</w>
                        <gloss><q>просо</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Sköld._Pam."/><biblScope>156</biblScope></bibl>),
                        <mentioned xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>уau</w>
                        <gloss><q>ячмень</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>yava-</w>
                        <gloss><q>злак</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>yava-</w>
                        <gloss><q>злак</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>ячмень</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>просо</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lt"><lang/>
                        <w>jāvas</w>
                        <gloss><q>злак</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>ζεά</w>
                        <gloss><q>полба</q></gloss></mentioned>. На русской почве сюда относят
                        <mentioned xml:lang="orv"><lang/>
                        <w>овинъ</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>овин</w></mentioned> (←* %ijavaina-%i ‘хлебный’, ‘предназначенный для
                    хлеба’). Из индоевропейских языков усвоено в некоторые угро-финские: <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fi"><lang/>
                        <w>jyvā</w>
                        <gloss><q>хлеб в зерне</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned
                        xml:lang="x-mordvin"><lang/>
                        <w>juv</w>
                        <gloss><q>мякина</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="udm"><lang/>
                        <w>yu</w>
                        <gloss><q>хлеб в зерне</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Jacobsohn"/><biblScope>118 прим.</biblScope></bibl>). Из
                    осетинского идет, очевидно, <mentioned xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>yav</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><lang/>
                        <w/>
                        <gloss><q>пшено</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>крупа</q></gloss></mentioned>. То, что древнейшее индоевропейское
                    название для злаков закрепилось в осетинском за просом, указывает на древность и
                    важность культуры проса на осетинской почве. В сарматскую эпоху „широко
                    распространено было просо, составлявшее один из важных продуктов питания у
                    меото-сарматских племен“ (<bibl><author>Н. Анфимов</author><biblScope>Древние
                            поселения Прикубанья. 1953, стр. 49</biblScope></bibl>). Ср. <ref
                        type="xr" target="#entry_mænæw"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_jæwgæf"
                            />.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>II
                            47, 90; Gr. 27</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>42</biblScope></bibl>. —
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Horn._Gr."
                            /><biblScope>96</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>59, 190</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">Traces back to Iranian *%iyava-%i. An Iranian and Indoeuropean
                    word. It was used to refer to different grasses. Cf. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ku"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ku"><w>yō</w></mentioned>,
                        <mentioned xml:lang="hac"><lang/>
                        <w>yāu</w></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_KPF"
                            /><biblScope>Abt. III, Bd. II, стр. 463</biblScope></bibl>), <mentioned
                        xml:lang="x-balochi"><lang/>
                        <w>jaw</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-balochi"><w>jō</w>
                        <gloss><q>barley</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ydg"><lang/>
                        <w>уōu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sgy"><lang/>
                        <w>уоu</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="isk"><lang/>
                        <w>уau</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="srh"><lang/>
                        <w>zau</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereals</q></gloss></mentioned> (?), <mentioned xml:lang="wbl"><lang/>
                        <w>zau</w></mentioned> id., <mentioned xml:lang="sgh"><lang/>
                        <w>jawaus</w>
                        <gloss><q>proso millet</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Sköld._Pam."/><biblScope>156</biblScope></bibl>),
                        <mentioned xml:lang="yai"><lang/>
                        <w>уau</w>
                        <gloss><q>barley</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>yava-</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereal</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><lang/>
                        <w>yava-</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereal</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>barley</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="sa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>proso millet</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="lt"><lang/>
                        <w>jāvas</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereal</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>ζεά</w>
                        <gloss><q>farro</q></gloss></mentioned>. <mentioned xml:lang="orv"><lang/>
                        <w>овинъ</w>
                        <gloss><q>barn</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>овин</w>
                        <gloss><q>barn</q></gloss></mentioned> (←* %ijavaina-%i ‘cereal’ (adj.),
                    ‘assigned for bread’) are attributed to this word as well. Some Ugro-Finnic
                    languages acquired it from Indo-European languages: <mentioned xml:lang="fi"><lang/>
                        <w>jyvā</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereals</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="x-mordvin"><lang/>
                        <w>juv</w>
                        <gloss><q>chaff</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="udm"><lang/>
                        <w>yu</w>
                        <gloss><q>cereals</q></gloss></mentioned> (<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Jacobsohn"/><biblScope>118 fn.</biblScope></bibl>). It is
                    evident that <mentioned xml:lang="ce"><lang/>
                        <w>yav</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><lang/>
                        <w/>
                        <gloss><q>millet</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="inh"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>groats</q></gloss></mentioned> come from Ossetic. The fact that
                    the oldest Indo-European name for cereals was reserved for proso millet in
                    Ossetic, indicates the antiquity and importance of proso millet in Ossetia. In
                    the Sarmatian era “millet was widespread, which was one of the important
                    foodstuffs of Meoto-Sarmatian tribes” (<bibl><author>N.
                            Anfimov.</author><biblScope>Drevnie poselenija Prikuban'ja [Ancient
                            settlements of the Kuban region]. 1953, p. 49</biblScope></bibl>). Ср.
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_mænæw"/>, <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_jæwgæf"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>II 47, 90; Gr.
                        27</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Hübschmann._Oss."/><biblScope>42</biblScope></bibl>. —
                            <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Horn._Gr."
                            /><biblScope>96</biblScope></bibl>. — <bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>59, 190</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
